1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
Delicious Vegan Sausages, Cheese
and Burgers - Vegusto.co.uk

2
00:01:57,350 --> 00:01:58,685
Mr. Wells?

3
00:02:00,031 --> 00:02:01,242
Mr. Wells?

4
00:02:02,563 --> 00:02:05,665
- Yes, Mrs. Schmidt?
- You've got company, Mr. Wells.

5
00:02:23,543 --> 00:02:25,743
That's some bender you've been on, pal.

6
00:02:25,847 --> 00:02:30,258
They're gonna have to put a night shift
on Jack Daniel's just to keep up with you.

7
00:02:34,929 --> 00:02:38,558
Mrs. Schmidt, call the police. 485-2581.

8
00:02:39,142 --> 00:02:43,396
Tell them to get an ambulance here fast.
Tell them we got a dying man.

9
00:02:52,113 --> 00:02:53,740
Police emergency?

10
00:02:55,616 --> 00:02:59,746
Can you send an ambulance?
We've got a man here. I think he's dying.

11
00:03:00,455 --> 00:03:03,249
The address is 1405 Beechwood.

12
00:03:03,499 --> 00:03:06,294
It's not as bad as the time in San Diego.

13
00:03:06,627 --> 00:03:10,256
Ira, I got a deal for us.

14
00:03:10,590 --> 00:03:12,383
Harry, who did it?

15
00:03:12,967 --> 00:03:15,803
It's a chance for us to make a lot of dough.

16
00:03:16,137 --> 00:03:18,723
Harry, you're dying. Tell me who did it.

17
00:03:19,599 --> 00:03:21,236
How did it happen?

18
00:03:21,340 --> 00:03:25,730
Don't worry, Ira, I'm cutting you in.
Fair deal.

19
00:03:26,856 --> 00:03:31,444
Just don't try to throw a scare into me.
It won't work.

20
00:03:33,154 --> 00:03:35,281
I'll lay it all out for you.

21
00:03:35,823 --> 00:03:39,285
Just get me to a hospital.

22
00:03:52,632 --> 00:03:54,342
God damn you, Harry!

23
00:03:57,470 --> 00:04:00,765
Letting somebody walk up
and drill you like that...

24
00:04:01,349 --> 00:04:02,767
point-blank.

25
00:04:05,395 --> 00:04:07,230
Nobody can palm a.45.

26
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:12,443
Jesus Christ.

27
00:04:13,444 --> 00:04:16,489
You never had the brains
God gave a common dog.

28
00:04:20,326 --> 00:04:22,453
Sorry you're going off, pal.

29
00:04:28,501 --> 00:04:30,586
You were real good company.

30
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:35,925
The best.

31
00:04:47,979 --> 00:04:49,480
The very best.

32
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:18,968
Margo, that's him.

33
00:05:19,427 --> 00:05:22,128
Jeez, Charles,
he doesn't look so hot to me.

34
00:05:22,232 --> 00:05:26,100
Let me tell you, kiddo,
Ira Wells used to be one of the greats.

35
00:05:29,062 --> 00:05:31,898
Whatever it is, Charlie, the answer is no.

36
00:05:32,482 --> 00:05:35,015
What do you mean no?
Did I say a word? Did I?

37
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:36,277
- No.
- Yeah.

38
00:05:36,611 --> 00:05:38,363
Ira, Margo. Margo, Ira.

39
00:05:38,696 --> 00:05:40,584
- Mr. Wells...
- Margo here's a pal of mine.

40
00:05:40,688 --> 00:05:43,534
How do you feel about cats?

41
00:05:44,118 --> 00:05:46,590
- I beg your pardon?
- Cats. How do you feel about them?

42
00:05:46,694 --> 00:05:48,164
I'm not sure.

43
00:05:48,456 --> 00:05:51,219
What I mean is that
somebody stole Winston.

44
00:05:51,323 --> 00:05:54,045
- Somebody stole who?
- Winston, my cat.

45
00:05:54,253 --> 00:05:56,537
Somebody stole him.
I have a picture of him.

46
00:05:56,641 --> 00:05:59,498
- What the hell is she talking about?
- I wanna show it to you.

47
00:05:59,603 --> 00:06:00,937
See, Brian stole Winston.

48
00:06:01,041 --> 00:06:04,232
And he said he would strangle him
if I don't pay him the money.

49
00:06:04,336 --> 00:06:06,735
Margo owes this guy $500 for a long time.

50
00:06:06,839 --> 00:06:09,425
Come on, Charles,
six months is hardly a long time.

51
00:06:09,529 --> 00:06:10,676
He gets PO'd at her...

52
00:06:10,780 --> 00:06:14,242
and steals the cat and threatens to kill it
if she doesn't give the dough.

53
00:06:14,346 --> 00:06:16,307
- So pay him.
- I can't pay him.

54
00:06:16,411 --> 00:06:18,288
I don't have the money to pay him.

55
00:06:18,392 --> 00:06:22,699
I see. You want me to find the guy
that stole your cat and bring it back, right?

56
00:06:22,824 --> 00:06:24,356
- Thanks, pal.
- He's easy to identify.

57
00:06:24,461 --> 00:06:26,859
I can't help you out.
Try the fire department.

58
00:06:26,963 --> 00:06:29,862
- I'm out of the business.
- His collar is...

59
00:06:29,966 --> 00:06:32,531
Come on, this is the kind of play
you can handle easy.

60
00:06:32,636 --> 00:06:34,909
Mr. Wells, if it's money...

61
00:06:35,013 --> 00:06:38,423
I had planned to offer you $25.
I have it right here.

62
00:06:39,007 --> 00:06:42,510
- Charlie, how long have I known you?
- I don't know, 16, 17 years.

63
00:06:43,344 --> 00:06:46,942
In all that time, did you
ever hear of Ira Wells taking a two-bit job?

64
00:06:47,046 --> 00:06:48,891
I heard what you said.

65
00:06:50,184 --> 00:06:52,186
This is not a two-bit job.

66
00:06:53,855 --> 00:06:57,452
I mean, if I offended you,
I'm very sorry, and I apologize...

67
00:06:57,556 --> 00:07:00,820
because I didn't mean to offend
the great Ira Wells.

68
00:07:01,195 --> 00:07:05,533
Charlie, I want you to know
I appreciate you coming to Harry's funeral.

69
00:07:06,534 --> 00:07:08,453
I enjoy talking to you.

70
00:07:09,328 --> 00:07:11,831
Maybe I don't act like it, but I do.

71
00:07:12,206 --> 00:07:15,168
There aren't many guys left
from the old days.

72
00:07:16,377 --> 00:07:20,590
I think you ought to teach your pal here
some respect for her elders.

73
00:07:22,967 --> 00:07:25,793
Yeah, well,
maybe you should learn a little respect...

74
00:07:25,897 --> 00:07:29,057
for other little creatures
that are walking under your...

75
00:07:29,557 --> 00:07:32,977
- Where are you headed?
- I'm going to the track, Hollywood Park.

76
00:07:34,896 --> 00:07:37,899
This little kitty is just a little honey bun!

77
00:07:39,233 --> 00:07:41,444
Give this little cat a break!

78
00:07:52,538 --> 00:07:54,697
<i>It's Bank Vault going away</i>
<i>by a length-and-a-half.</i>

79
00:07:54,801 --> 00:07:58,617
<i>Wild Chase is second by four lengths.</i>
<i>Easy Victor, on the inside, is third.</i>

80
00:07:58,722 --> 00:08:00,682
<i>Kewpie Doll and Top Target are tied.</i>

81
00:08:00,786 --> 00:08:04,373
<i>The rest of the field is well back. Down</i>
<i>the course Bank Vault pulls away.</i>

82
00:08:04,477 --> 00:08:05,791
<i>Wild Chase is leading.</i>

83
00:08:05,895 --> 00:08:08,805
<i>Easy Victor and Kewpie Doll</i>
<i>unable to close any ground.</i>

84
00:08:15,436 --> 00:08:17,980
<i>... and Kewpie Doll is the fourth horse.</i>

85
00:08:18,147 --> 00:08:21,891
<i>Timing the race for six furlongs,</i>
<i>covering three-quarters of a mile...</i>

86
00:08:21,995 --> 00:08:25,519
<i>one minute, ten seconds flat.</i>
<i>In the winner's circle is Bank Vault...</i>

87
00:08:25,624 --> 00:08:29,210
<i>with Hollywood Park's leading apprentice</i>
<i>jockey, Benny de Angelino...</i>

88
00:08:29,315 --> 00:08:31,254
<i>getting his fifth in the current leading.</i>

89
00:08:31,358 --> 00:08:34,111
<i>And for those looking for a hot bet</i>
<i>on Friday the 13th...</i>

90
00:08:34,215 --> 00:08:37,917
<i>this might have been the horse</i>
<i>they were looking for luck on the 13th.</i>

91
00:08:47,969 --> 00:08:50,555
All right, Charlie, give out with it.

92
00:08:51,389 --> 00:08:53,974
I thought you was going to the track.

93
00:08:55,309 --> 00:08:57,884
How long has it been
since I've seen you, Charlie?

94
00:08:57,988 --> 00:08:59,980
Close to a year, isn't it?

95
00:09:01,606 --> 00:09:04,401
Somebody puts the freeze
on Harry Regan...

96
00:09:04,902 --> 00:09:08,416
next thing I know, you show up
at Harry's funeral with some dolly...

97
00:09:08,521 --> 00:09:12,493
and a song and dance about a stolen cat,
and all that hot comedy.

98
00:09:13,828 --> 00:09:16,289
What's it all got to do with Harry?

99
00:09:20,793 --> 00:09:22,576
Harry was working for the dolly.

100
00:09:22,681 --> 00:09:26,247
Are you telling me that Harry
got himself killed on account of some cat?

101
00:09:26,351 --> 00:09:27,508
Listen.

102
00:09:29,135 --> 00:09:31,763
I know Margo maybe six or seven years.

103
00:09:32,847 --> 00:09:34,547
Used to be a client of mine.

104
00:09:34,651 --> 00:09:39,312
One night, a couple of weeks ago, she
comes into this bar where I'm working...

105
00:09:40,438 --> 00:09:43,514
Just sort of temporary.
The talent business is slow.

106
00:09:43,618 --> 00:09:48,102
Anyway, it turns out that she's mad as hell
about this guy stealing her cat.

107
00:09:48,206 --> 00:09:49,530
I'm listening...

108
00:09:50,782 --> 00:09:53,023
and all of a sudden
I remember Harry Regan.

109
00:09:53,128 --> 00:09:56,287
And I think to myself,
"He's still in the business...

110
00:09:56,537 --> 00:09:59,540
"if there's any business left for him to do."

111
00:10:01,250 --> 00:10:02,835
He took the job.

112
00:10:04,629 --> 00:10:08,038
So he finds this guy that stole the cat
and starts to follow him.

113
00:10:08,143 --> 00:10:10,916
- Yeah.
- Who is this guy Harry was tailing?

114
00:10:11,021 --> 00:10:13,888
I wouldn't know him
from a hole in my sock.

115
00:10:14,263 --> 00:10:15,515
The dolly?

116
00:10:18,017 --> 00:10:21,521
- The dolly? What about her?
- Where does she live, Charlie?

117
00:10:23,231 --> 00:10:25,400
Some place called La Paloma...

118
00:10:26,651 --> 00:10:28,945
over on Franklin, near Vermont.

119
00:10:31,114 --> 00:10:33,366
That's where you live, isn't it, Charlie?

120
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:35,243
Yeah.

121
00:10:48,631 --> 00:10:51,384
<i>As we begin to meditate...</i>

122
00:10:52,093 --> 00:10:53,970
<i>take a deep breath.</i>

123
00:10:55,054 --> 00:10:57,755
Charlotte, listen to me.
Tonight is important.

124
00:10:57,859 --> 00:10:59,965
I don't want you to get uptight about it.

125
00:11:00,070 --> 00:11:03,698
Because this guy books
a lot of Holiday Inns all over the country.

126
00:11:03,803 --> 00:11:05,429
I think it's a good place to start.

127
00:11:05,533 --> 00:11:08,516
I mean, it's a good place to work out
a lot of problems.

128
00:11:08,620 --> 00:11:11,727
You're gonna be absolutely terrific tonight.
Who's taking you?

129
00:11:11,831 --> 00:11:14,532
- What's he gonna wear?
<i>- Imagine the joy...</i>

130
00:11:15,116 --> 00:11:18,536
Wait. I'll tell you what.
I think he should wait outside.

131
00:11:19,370 --> 00:11:20,861
No, because that's very important.

132
00:11:20,966 --> 00:11:24,959
I'm telling you, the entire picture,
the entire impression, is important.

133
00:11:27,045 --> 00:11:30,496
Charlotte, this is another
self-destructive act, in my opinion.

134
00:11:30,600 --> 00:11:33,499
Listen, if I am gonna handle your career...

135
00:11:33,603 --> 00:11:36,043
and if I am going to be...
Wait a second, Charlotte.

136
00:11:36,147 --> 00:11:39,932
Charlotte, listen, I got to go.
No. Somebody just walked in.

137
00:11:40,266 --> 00:11:43,353
I'll see you at 10:30.
You're gonna be terrific.

138
00:11:43,603 --> 00:11:45,938
Think positive. Okay, bye-bye.

139
00:11:47,482 --> 00:11:50,307
Why don't you just come in
and make yourself comfortable?

140
00:11:50,412 --> 00:11:55,156
<i>... descending into the boundless water...</i>

141
00:11:56,866 --> 00:11:58,618
<i>as it rises over...</i>

142
00:11:58,951 --> 00:12:01,913
<i>your tired, weary body.</i>

143
00:12:03,623 --> 00:12:05,750
<i>You begin to relax.</i>

144
00:12:06,209 --> 00:12:09,201
Harry Regan was a pal of mine
close to 24 years.

145
00:12:09,306 --> 00:12:12,840
Whoever it was that killed him
is gonna be goddamn sorry.

146
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:16,969
Mr. Wells, I can understand
your feeling that way.

147
00:12:17,261 --> 00:12:20,723
I mean, as an actress,
I understand it as a motivation.

148
00:12:21,015 --> 00:12:25,478
- What about this guy who took your cat?
- Brian Hemphill.

149
00:12:26,020 --> 00:12:30,650
He's this guy, he's really sort of a tuna.
He just hangs around, you know.

150
00:12:31,818 --> 00:12:35,738
And we used to have this thing going,
kind of a sexual interlude.

151
00:12:36,322 --> 00:12:38,700
It never really came to anything.

152
00:12:39,701 --> 00:12:42,193
Now Brian and his friend
sometimes give me money...

153
00:12:42,297 --> 00:12:45,206
to schlep things to this guy in Bakersfield.

154
00:12:45,790 --> 00:12:48,710
- Things? What things?
- You know, things.

155
00:12:49,127 --> 00:12:52,296
Material things.
I mean, worldly possessions:

156
00:12:52,630 --> 00:12:56,801
Washing machines, TV sets,
clock radios. Things.

157
00:12:56,926 --> 00:13:00,252
Did it ever cross your mind
these things might be hot?

158
00:13:00,357 --> 00:13:04,225
Who's to know? I mean,
I'm not by nature a curious person.

159
00:13:04,600 --> 00:13:05,674
I'll bet.

160
00:13:05,779 --> 00:13:09,105
- I mean, go with the flow.
- That's what I always say.

161
00:13:10,064 --> 00:13:12,723
This guy in Bakersfield,
he paid you off in cash, right?

162
00:13:12,827 --> 00:13:13,849
Yes.

163
00:13:13,954 --> 00:13:17,603
Then you'd bring the dough to this punk,
Brian, then you'd get your cut?

164
00:13:17,707 --> 00:13:18,750
Yes.

165
00:13:18,875 --> 00:13:22,525
Only on this last trip, you decided you
wanna keep the money yourself, right?

166
00:13:22,629 --> 00:13:26,153
So Brian gets mad because
he wants his dough. So he steals your cat.

167
00:13:26,258 --> 00:13:28,823
- And you go crying to Harry Regan.
- It was just a loan.

168
00:13:28,927 --> 00:13:33,755
I did not take the money, it was a loan,
just till I get my dress business going.

169
00:13:34,505 --> 00:13:38,134
- Your dress business?
- I design all the clothes I make.

170
00:13:39,802 --> 00:13:43,462
- I thought you were an actress.
- Are you kidding? I did the whole star trip.

171
00:13:43,566 --> 00:13:46,173
I just never could learn
how to push myself, you know.

172
00:13:46,278 --> 00:13:50,063
I don't like to go begging.
I don't want anybody to do me any favors.

173
00:13:50,271 --> 00:13:53,775
I just never could learn
how to play the Hollywood game.

174
00:13:54,108 --> 00:13:57,487
My shrink says
that I'm a very conflicted personality.

175
00:13:57,653 --> 00:13:59,614
- Jesus Christ.
- But my astrologist...

176
00:13:59,739 --> 00:14:01,574
What is that supposed to mean?

177
00:14:01,699 --> 00:14:04,879
Back in the '40s, this town was crawling
with dollies like you.

178
00:14:04,984 --> 00:14:08,279
Good-looking cokeheads trying
their damnedest to act tough as hell.

179
00:14:08,383 --> 00:14:11,417
I got news for you:
They did it better back then.

180
00:14:11,542 --> 00:14:15,171
This town doesn't change.
They just push the names around.

181
00:14:16,297 --> 00:14:19,967
Same dames,
screwing up their lives just the same way.

182
00:14:21,719 --> 00:14:25,337
All right. What about this guy Brian?
Where can I find him?

183
00:14:25,442 --> 00:14:27,767
Who's to know. He just hangs around.

184
00:14:28,309 --> 00:14:31,343
- Where is around?
- Around is around.

185
00:14:31,448 --> 00:14:33,888
I mean, around is no particular place.

186
00:14:33,992 --> 00:14:37,892
The only time I hear from him is when he
calls me up to torment me about my cat.

187
00:14:37,996 --> 00:14:40,978
The next time he calls you up,
I want you to set up a meet.

188
00:14:41,082 --> 00:14:42,365
All right.

189
00:14:43,741 --> 00:14:47,495
Mr. Wells, listen,
I don't want you to get the wrong idea...

190
00:14:47,912 --> 00:14:52,667
- about me schlepping those things...
- Doll, I'm not interested in your life story.

191
00:14:52,959 --> 00:14:55,753
Just set up a meet with your friend Brian.

192
00:15:03,511 --> 00:15:05,555
Yes? I'm coming.

193
00:15:06,431 --> 00:15:07,765
Just a minute.

194
00:15:09,350 --> 00:15:11,258
I don't care what you say, you understand?

195
00:15:11,363 --> 00:15:13,844
- Yes?
- Hi, I'm Margo Sperling.

196
00:15:13,949 --> 00:15:16,357
We'd like to talk to your husband.

197
00:15:16,482 --> 00:15:19,152
No, my husband passed on
seven years ago.

198
00:15:19,318 --> 00:15:21,237
What's going on in here?

199
00:15:22,822 --> 00:15:25,272
We were playing canasta
right there in the living room.

200
00:15:25,377 --> 00:15:27,358
Kid, the you-know-what has hit the fan.

201
00:15:27,462 --> 00:15:30,694
Look, I wouldn't make a federal case
out of everything, Charlie.

202
00:15:30,799 --> 00:15:34,406
Mrs. Schmidt, would you leave us alone
for a couple of minutes?

203
00:15:34,511 --> 00:15:38,546
I have some personal business
to talk over with these people.

204
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:40,287
Of course, Mr. Wells.

205
00:15:40,392 --> 00:15:43,509
- It was very nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

206
00:15:43,718 --> 00:15:47,180
Anytime, Mr. Wells,
your friends are more than welcome.

207
00:15:47,347 --> 00:15:50,641
- Thank you.
- I like the color of your sweater.

208
00:15:51,768 --> 00:15:53,853
- Thank you.
- Very much.

209
00:15:57,732 --> 00:16:00,933
- The man's a killer, you ding-a-ling!
- Don't call me a ding-a-ling!

210
00:16:01,037 --> 00:16:02,111
Hold it!

211
00:16:02,612 --> 00:16:04,666
This happens to be where I live, okay?

212
00:16:04,770 --> 00:16:08,482
It may not look like a hell of a lot to you,
but it suits me.

213
00:16:08,587 --> 00:16:11,819
Now, Mrs. Schmidt, that's my landlady,
we get along just fine.

214
00:16:11,923 --> 00:16:15,239
At least we did until a few days ago.
If you two would simmer down...

215
00:16:15,343 --> 00:16:17,220
tell me what's going on, I'd appreciate it.

216
00:16:17,324 --> 00:16:19,910
Okay. You wanted to take
a meeting with Brian, right?

217
00:16:20,015 --> 00:16:21,579
So he called me.

218
00:16:21,683 --> 00:16:24,853
I'm listening to him carefully
because I've known him a long time.

219
00:16:24,957 --> 00:16:28,043
And Brian's not very evolved.
In fact, he's rather de-evolved.

220
00:16:28,148 --> 00:16:31,797
I was talking to him, and I'm very sensitive
to the vibrations he gives out.

221
00:16:31,901 --> 00:16:33,591
Because I know what karma he has...

222
00:16:33,695 --> 00:16:37,011
- What is she talking about?
- She said you was looking for this guy...

223
00:16:37,115 --> 00:16:40,201
- because of what happened to Harry.
- That's what I said.

224
00:16:40,306 --> 00:16:42,892
She said if he didn't come here
you'd come gunning for him.

225
00:16:42,996 --> 00:16:46,041
- That's right.
- The punk that nailed Harry's coming here?

226
00:16:46,145 --> 00:16:48,731
